Public health decision making is a complicated process because of complex inputs and group decision making.
This course is designed to provide knowledge and skills about different methodological approaches to conducting assessment on the field of public health. The course presents the use of methods of primary data collection (e.g., randomised controlled trials) supplemented by the use of secondary data (e.g., systematic review/metanalysis); policy and program assessment; qualitative methods for public health assessment. The major emphasis of the course  is placed upon "real-world" public health  assessment examples (on infectious diseases, chronic diseases, public health practice - vaccination, and selected exposure - alcohol use)Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course introduces principles of evidence-based pubcli health / health practice.
Specifically: 
1. Define evidence-based public health and become familiar with key concepts in evidence-based public health;
2. Become familiar with key methods (incl study designs) for producing evidence for public health practice;
3. Apply key concepts to searching and evaluating the public health literature.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Students will be expected - To be able to seek, analyze and present evidence-based information on different health problems, interventions and public health / health services
